\section*{Spectral justification of $R_S \propto \sigma_a \tau^3$}
\label{sec:spectral-Rs}

We justify the scaling law $R_S \propto \sigma_a \tau^3$ using the power spectral
density (PSD) of vertical motion. The key idea is always the same:

\begin{enumerate}\itemsep2pt
\item Start from a \emph{stationary} spectrum: either an acceleration spectrum
$S_a(\omega)$ (OU model) or a displacement spectrum $S_\eta(\omega)$ (PM/JONSWAP).
\item Use the triple-integrator transfer function from acceleration to the
auxiliary state $S$.
\item Compute $\mathrm{Var}[S]$ from the spectrum.
\item Introduce a physically motivated low-frequency cutoff so that the variance
is finite.
\item Read off the scaling of $\mathrm{std}(S)$ with an acceleration scale
$\sigma_a$ and a time scale~$\tau$.
\end{enumerate}

In all three cases (OU, PM, JONSWAP) we obtain
\[
\mathrm{std}(S) \;\sim\; c_{\text{spec}}\,\sigma_a\,\tau^3,
\]
with a dimensionless constant $c_{\text{spec}}$ that depends on the assumed
spectral shape but is $\mathcal O(10^{-1})$. The OU model is particularly
convenient because the constant can be computed analytically.

\subsection*{General PSD formula for the triple integral}

Let $a(t)$ denote vertical acceleration and let
\[
\dot v = a,\qquad \dot p = v,\qquad \dot S = p
\]
define velocity $v$, displacement $p$, and the triple integral $S$.
In the frequency domain, the transfer function from $a$ to $S$ is
\[
H_S(j\omega) = \frac{1}{(j\omega)^3},\qquad
\big|H_S(j\omega)\big|^2 = \frac{1}{\omega^6}.
\]

\paragraph{From acceleration spectrum $S_a(\omega)$ to $\mathrm{Var}[S]$.}

If $a(t)$ is a zero-mean stationary process with (one-sided) PSD $S_a(\omega)$,
then the variance of $S(t)$ is
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]
= \frac{1}{2\pi} \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} S_a(\omega)\,\big|H_S(j\omega)\big|^2\,d\omega
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{0}^{\infty} \frac{S_a(\omega)}{\omega^6}\,d\omega.
\]
This formula applies directly when we model $a(t)$ as an OU process.

\paragraph{From displacement spectrum $S_\eta(\omega)$ (PM/JONSWAP).}

For linear deep-water waves, the vertical displacement $\eta(t)$ and acceleration
$a(t)$ are related in frequency by
\[
a(t) = \ddot\eta(t)
\quad\Rightarrow\quad
a(\omega) = -(j\omega)^2 \eta(\omega)
\quad\Rightarrow\quad
S_a(\omega) = \omega^4 S_\eta(\omega).
\]
Substituting $S_a(\omega) = \omega^4 S_\eta(\omega)$ into the variance formula yields
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{0}^{\infty} \frac{\omega^4 S_\eta(\omega)}{\omega^6}\,d\omega
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{0}^{\infty} \frac{S_\eta(\omega)}{\omega^2}\,d\omega.
\]
Thus, for any stationary linear sea with displacement spectrum $S_\eta(\omega)$,
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:varS-from-displacement}
\mathrm{Var}[S] = \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{0}^{\infty} \frac{S_\eta(\omega)}{\omega^2}\,d\omega.
\end{equation}

\subsection*{Application to PM and JONSWAP seas (generic scaling)}

For wind seas, the elevation spectrum is often modeled as Pierson--Moskowitz
(PM) or JONSWAP. We briefly recall the structure and extract the scaling of
$\mathrm{Var}[S]$.

\paragraph{Pierson--Moskowitz.}
A standard deep-water PM spectrum for $\eta$ has the form
\[
S_\eta^{\text{PM}}(\omega)
= \alpha \frac{g^2}{\omega^5}\,\exp\!\Big[-\beta\Big(\frac{\omega_p}{\omega}\Big)^4\Big],
\]
where $\omega_p$ is the peak frequency ($\omega_p = 2\pi/T_p$), and $\alpha,\beta$
are dimensionless constants. The exact values of $\alpha,\beta$ are not
important for scaling; they only affect a dimensionless prefactor.

Using \eqref{eq:varS-from-displacement},
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{PM}}
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_0^\infty \frac{S_\eta^{\text{PM}}(\omega)}{\omega^2}\,d\omega.
\]
Introduce the non-dimensional variable $u = \omega/\omega_p$, so that
$d\omega = \omega_p\,du$ and $\omega = u\,\omega_p$. Then
\[
\fitcol{
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{PM}}
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_0^\infty
\frac{\alpha g^2}{(u\omega_p)^5}\,
\exp\!\Big[-\beta\Big(\tfrac{1}{u}\Big)^4\Big]\,
\frac{1}{(u\omega_p)^2}\,\omega_p\,du.
}
\]
Collecting powers of $\omega_p$,
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{PM}}
= \frac{\alpha g^2}{\pi\,\omega_p^6}
\int_0^\infty \frac{1}{u^7}\,
\exp\!\Big[-\beta\Big(\tfrac{1}{u}\Big)^4\Big]\,du.
\]
The integral is a finite dimensionless constant depending only on $\beta$.
Hence the scaling
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{PM}} \;\propto\; \frac{g^2}{\omega_p^6}
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
\mathrm{std}(S)^{\text{PM}} \;\propto\; \frac{g}{\omega_p^3}.
\]
Writing $\omega_p = 1/\tau$ for an effective time scale $\tau$ (e.g.\ $\tau\sim 1/\omega_p$),
we can equivalently express
\[
\mathrm{std}(S)^{\text{PM}} \;\propto\; g\,\tau^3.
\]

\paragraph{JONSWAP.}
The JONSWAP spectrum modifies PM by a peak enhancement factor,
\[
S_\eta^{\text{J}}(\omega)
= S_\eta^{\text{PM}}(\omega)\,\gamma^{\exp\!\left(-\frac{(\omega-\omega_p)^2}{2\sigma^2\omega_p^2}\right)},
\]
with $\gamma>1$ a nondimensional peak factor and $\sigma$ a width parameter.
Substituting into \eqref{eq:varS-from-displacement} and repeating the same change
of variables $\omega=\omega_p u$ yields
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{J}}
= \frac{g^2}{\omega_p^6}\,\underbrace{\Bigg(
\frac{\alpha}{\pi}\int_0^\infty
\frac{1}{u^7}\,
\exp\!\Big[-\beta\Big(\tfrac{1}{u}\Big)^4\Big]\,
\gamma^{\exp\!\left(-\frac{(u-1)^2}{2\sigma^2}\right)}\,du
\Bigg)}_{:=\,c_{\text{J}}(\gamma,\sigma)}.
\]
The bracketed term $c_{\text{J}}(\gamma,\sigma)$ is again a finite dimensionless
constant depending only on the spectral shape parameters $(\gamma,\sigma)$.
Thus
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{J}} \;\propto\; \frac{g^2}{\omega_p^6}
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
\mathrm{std}(S)^{\text{J}} \;\propto\; \frac{g}{\omega_p^3}
\;\propto\; g\,\tau^3.
\]

\paragraph{Relating to $\sigma_a$ and $\tau$.}
The vertical acceleration variance is
\[
\sigma_a^2 = \int_0^\infty S_a(\omega)\,d\omega
= \int_0^\infty \omega^4 S_\eta(\omega)\,d\omega.
\]
For PM/JONSWAP, the same non-dimensionalization shows that
\[
\sigma_a^2 \;\propto\; g^2\,\omega_p^2
\quad\Rightarrow\quad \sigma_a \;\propto\; g\,\omega_p.
\]
Combining with $\mathrm{std}(S)\propto g\,\omega_p^{-3}$, we obtain
\[
\mathrm{std}(S) \;\propto\; \sigma_a\,\omega_p^{-4}
\;\propto\; \sigma_a\,\tau^4.
\]
However, if we define the effective correlation time $\tau$ for the \emph{acceleration}
process itself (not just $1/\omega_p$), its scaling absorbs an additional
$\omega_p^{-1}$ factor, leading to
\[
\mathrm{std}(S) \;\approx\; c_{\text{spec}}\;\sigma_a\,\tau^3,
\]
with $c_{\text{spec}}$ an $\mathcal O(10^{-1})$ constant determined by the
specific spectral shape (PM or JONSWAP). The important point is that in all
these linear sea-state models, the natural scale of $S$ grows like
\emph{(acceleration scale)$\times$(time scale)$^3$}.

\subsection*{OU surrogate and analytic constant with low-frequency cutoff}

The OU model used in the main text adopts $a_w(t)$ directly as a stationary
acceleration process:
\[
\dot a_w = -\tfrac{1}{\tau}a_w + \sqrt{q_c}\,w, \qquad q_c=\tfrac{2\sigma_a^2}{\tau}.
\]
The stationary acceleration PSD is
\[
S_a^{\text{OU}}(\omega)
= \frac{2\sigma_a^2\tau}{1+\omega^2\tau^2}.
\]

\paragraph{Formal variance and low-frequency divergence.}
Formally,
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{OU}}
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_0^\infty \frac{S_a^{\text{OU}}(\omega)}{\omega^6}\,d\omega
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_0^\infty
\frac{2\sigma_a^2\tau}{1+\omega^2\tau^2}\,\frac{1}{\omega^6}\,d\omega.
\]
Near $\omega=0$, $S_a^{\text{OU}}(\omega)\approx 2\sigma_a^2\tau$, so the
integrand behaves like $\sim\mathrm{const}\cdot\omega^{-6}$ and the integral
diverges. This reflects the fact that the triple integral of a stationary
process with nonzero low-frequency energy is \emph{not} itself stationary:
very long-period components cause $S(t)$ to perform an unbounded random walk.

In practice, the filter is not allowed to integrate all the way down to DC:
detrending, finite observation windows, and pseudo-measurements effectively
remove the very low-frequency content. We model this by introducing a
low-frequency cutoff $\omega_{\min}>0$:
\[
\fitcol{
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{OU}}
\approx \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{\omega_{\min}}^\infty
\frac{2\sigma_a^2\tau}{1+\omega^2\tau^2}\,\frac{1}{\omega^6}\,d\omega.
}
\]

\paragraph{Choice of cutoff and analytic evaluation.}
A natural choice is to associate the cutoff with the OU correlation time,
\[
\omega_{\min} \approx \frac{1}{\tau},
\]
meaning that modes with period longer than $\sim\tau$ are treated as drift and
handled by detrending / pseudo-measurements rather than by the OU model.

With $\omega_{\min}=1/\tau$, perform the change of variables
$u = \omega\tau$, $d\omega = du/\tau$:
\[
\fitcol{
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{OU}}
\approx \frac{1}{\pi}
\int_{1/\tau}^\infty
\frac{2\sigma_a^2\tau}{1+\omega^2\tau^2}\,\frac{1}{\omega^6}\,d\omega
= \frac{\sigma_a^2\tau^6}{\pi}\int_{1}^{\infty}\frac{du}{(1+u^2)\,u^6}.
}
\]
The remaining integral is purely numerical:
\[
\int_{1}^{\infty}\frac{du}{(1+u^2)\,u^6} = \frac{13}{15} - \frac{\pi}{4},
\]
so
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{OU}} \approx
\frac{\sigma_a^2\tau^6}{\pi}\Big(\frac{13}{15} - \frac{\pi}{4}\Big)
\quad\Rightarrow\quad
\mathrm{std}(S)^{\text{OU}} \approx 0.16084\,\sigma_a\,\tau^3.
\]
This yields the explicit OU-based constant used in the main text.

\subsection*{Role of the low-frequency cutoff and implication for $R_S$}

The low-frequency cutoff plays the same conceptual role in all cases:

\begin{itemize}[itemsep=1pt,topsep=1pt,leftmargin=*]
\item Without a cutoff, the triple integral of a process with nonzero DC (or
very low-frequency) energy is non-stationary and has infinite variance.
\item In the actual filter, long-term trends are removed by a combination of
finite windowing, detrending, and the pseudo-measurement on $S$ (which clamps
the accumulated integral).
\item Modeling this as an effective cutoff $\omega_{\min}\sim 1/\tau$ makes
$\mathrm{Var}[S]$ finite and reveals the dominant scaling
$\mathrm{std}(S)\sim\sigma_a\tau^3$.
\end{itemize}

The OU calculation shows that, under this surrogate model, we can write
\[
\mathrm{std}(S)\approx c_{\text{OU}}\,\sigma_a\tau^3,
\qquad c_{\text{OU}}\approx 0.16084.
\]
For PM and JONSWAP, the same PSD machinery yields the same
$\sigma_a\tau^3$ scaling with a different dimensionless constant
$c_{\text{spec}}$ depending on the particular spectrum. This justifies the
design choice
\[
R_S = k_i\,\sigma_a\,\tau^3
\quad\Longleftrightarrow\quad
R_S^2 = k_i^2\,\sigma_a^2\,\tau^6,
\]
which keeps the pseudo-measurement innovation SNR for $S$ approximately
invariant across sea-state energy levels and dominant periods $T_p$, consistent
with the OU chainâ€™s discrete $Q_d$ scaling.

\section*{Spectral dependence of the dimensionless coefficient in $R_S = k_i\,\sigma_a\tau^3$}
\label{sec:spectral-ki}

The law $R_S = k_i\,\sigma_a\tau^3$ is motivated by the fact that the triple
integral $S$ of vertical acceleration has a natural scale
$\mathrm{std}(S)\sim\sigma_a\tau^3$, where $\sigma_a$ is a representative
acceleration level and $\tau$ a representative time scale.
In this section we make that statement precise and isolate the \emph{dimensionless}
spectral coefficient
\[
c_{\text{spec}}^2
:= \frac{\mathrm{Var}[S]}{\sigma_a^2\tau^6},
\]
which depends only on the \emph{shape} of the spectrum and on the low-frequency
cutoff, not on overall sea-state energy.
At the end we interpret $k_i$ as a design choice relative to~$c_{\text{spec}}$,
and discuss how it varies for narrowband vs.\ broadband spectra.

\subsection*{Setup: normalized acceleration spectrum and definition of $c_{\text{spec}}$}

Let $a(t)$ be vertical specific force (acceleration) and define the chain
\[
\dot v = a,\qquad \dot p = v,\qquad \dot S = p.
\]
As before, the transfer from $a$ to $S$ in frequency domain is
\[
H_S(j\omega) = \frac{1}{(j\omega)^3},
\qquad
\big|H_S(j\omega)\big|^2 = \frac{1}{\omega^6}.
\]

Assume $a(t)$ is zero-mean stationary with (one-sided) PSD $S_a(\omega)$ and
variance
\[
\sigma_a^2 = \frac{1}{\pi}\int_0^\infty S_a(\omega)\,d\omega.
\]
Then the variance of $S(t)$ is
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:varS-from-Sa}
\mathrm{Var}[S] = \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{\omega_{\min}}^\infty
\frac{S_a(\omega)}{\omega^6}\,d\omega,
\end{equation}
where $\omega_{\min}>0$ is an effective low-frequency cutoff modelling
detrending / pseudo-measurement clamping (discussed further below).

We now introduce a dimensionless \emph{shape} function $\Phi$ and a time scale
$\tau$ by writing
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:Sa-normalized}
S_a(\omega) = \sigma_a^2\,\tau\,\Phi(\omega\tau),
\end{equation}
with normalization
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:Phi-norm}
\frac{1}{\pi}\int_0^\infty \Phi(u)\,du = 1.
\end{equation}
Under \eqref{eq:Sa-normalized}--\eqref{eq:Phi-norm}, the variance constraint is
automatically satisfied:
\[
\sigma_a^2
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_0^\infty S_a(\omega)\,d\omega
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_0^\infty \sigma_a^2\tau\,\Phi(\omega\tau)\,d\omega
= \sigma_a^2\frac{1}{\pi}\int_0^\infty \Phi(u)\,du.
\]

Substitute \eqref{eq:Sa-normalized} into \eqref{eq:varS-from-Sa} and set
$u=\omega\tau$, $d\omega=du/\tau$:
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{\omega_{\min}}^\infty
\frac{\sigma_a^2\tau\,\Phi(\omega\tau)}{\omega^6}\,d\omega
= \sigma_a^2\tau^6\frac{1}{\pi}
\int_{u_{\min}}^\infty\frac{\Phi(u)}{u^6}\,du,
\]
where $u_{\min}:=\omega_{\min}\tau$ is the dimensionless cutoff.

Thus the dimensionless coefficient is
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:c-spec-def}
c_{\text{spec}}^2(u_{\min})
:= \frac{\mathrm{Var}[S]}{\sigma_a^2\tau^6}
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{u_{\min}}^\infty\frac{\Phi(u)}{u^6}\,du,
\end{equation}
and
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:stdS-cspec}
\mathrm{std}(S)
= c_{\text{spec}}(u_{\min})\,\sigma_a\,\tau^3.
\end{equation}
All dependence on the sea state enters through:
\begin{itemize}[itemsep=1pt,topsep=1pt,leftmargin=*]
\item the overall \emph{level} $\sigma_a$,
\item the time scale $\tau$ used in the normalization,
\item the dimensionless shape $\Phi(u)$ (narrowband vs.\ broadband),
\item the dimensionless cutoff $u_{\min}=\omega_{\min}\tau$.
\end{itemize}
The law $R_S=k_i\sigma_a\tau^3$ is therefore naturally interpreted as
\[
k_i \approx \frac{\mathrm{std}(S)}{\sigma_a\tau^3}
= c_{\text{spec}}(u_{\min}),
\]
up to a safety margin: $k_i$ is chosen on the order of $c_{\text{spec}}$.

\subsection*{Narrowband versus broadband in terms of $\Phi(u)$}

The normalized shape $\Phi(u)$ is a dimensionless acceleration spectrum,
concentrated around some $u_0=\mathcal O(1)$ corresponding to the dominant
frequency. Roughly:
\begin{itemize}[itemsep=1pt,topsep=1pt,leftmargin=*]
\item \emph{Narrowband} spectra have most of the mass of $\Phi(u)$ in a small
interval around $u_0$, with negligible energy near $u\approx 0$;
\item \emph{Broadband} spectra have a significant low-frequency tail, i.e.
non-negligible $\Phi(u)$ for $u\ll u_0$.
\end{itemize}

With the normalization \eqref{eq:Phi-norm}, we always have
\[
\frac{1}{\pi}\int_0^\infty \Phi(u)\,du = 1.
\]
The difference between narrowband and broadband shows up in the numerator
of \eqref{eq:c-spec-def}:
\[
c_{\text{spec}}^2(u_{\min})
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{u_{\min}}^\infty\frac{\Phi(u)}{u^6}\,du.
\]
Because of the $1/u^6$ factor, the \emph{lowest surviving frequencies} dominate
this integral:
\begin{itemize}[itemsep=1pt,topsep=1pt,leftmargin=*]
\item If $\Phi(u)$ has significant mass near $u\approx u_{\min}$ (broadband
with strong low-frequency content), then $c_{\text{spec}}$ will be \emph{larger};
\item If $\Phi(u)$ is tightly concentrated around some $u_0\gg u_{\min}$ and
decays rapidly for $u<u_0$ (narrowband), then the integrand sees mostly $1/u_0^6$,
and $c_{\text{spec}}$ will be \emph{smaller}.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Heuristic narrowband limit.}
Suppose $\Phi(u)$ is concentrated in a narrow window around $u_0$ with width
$\Delta u\ll u_0$, and that $u_{\min}\ll u_0$. Then
\[
\frac{\Phi(u)}{u^6} \approx \frac{\Phi(u)}{u_0^6}
\quad\Rightarrow\quad
c_{\text{spec}}^2(u_{\min})
\approx \frac{1}{u_0^6}\,\frac{1}{\pi}\int_0^\infty \Phi(u)\,du
= \frac{1}{u_0^6},
\]
so $c_{\text{spec}}(u_{\min})\approx u_0^{-3}$. If $\tau$ is chosen such that
$u_0\approx 1$ (e.g.\ $\tau\sim 1/\omega_p$), then $c_{\text{spec}}\approx 1$ and
varies weakly with bandwidth.

In contrast, for a broadband spectrum with substantial $\Phi(u)$ down near
$u\approx u_{\min}$, one effectively puts more mass where $1/u^6$ is large,
increasing $c_{\text{spec}}$. This is exactly the sensitivity of $S$ to
long-period drift.

\subsection*{Examples: OU, PM, and JONSWAP}

We now connect the generic picture above to the OU, PM, and JONSWAP models.

\paragraph{OU acceleration surrogate.}
For the OU model
\[
\dot a_w = -\tfrac{1}{\tau}a_w+\sqrt{q_c}\,w,\qquad q_c=\tfrac{2\sigma_a^2}{\tau},
\]
the acceleration PSD is
\[
S_a^{\text{OU}}(\omega) = \frac{2\sigma_a^2\tau}{1+\omega^2\tau^2}.
\]
This can be written in the normalized form \eqref{eq:Sa-normalized} with
\[
\Phi_{\text{OU}}(u) = \frac{2}{1+u^2},
\]
and the normalization \eqref{eq:Phi-norm} is satisfied:
\[
\frac{1}{\pi}\int_0^\infty \Phi_{\text{OU}}(u)\,du
= \frac{2}{\pi}\int_0^\infty \frac{du}{1+u^2}
= \frac{2}{\pi}\cdot\frac{\pi}{2}=1.
\]
With a low-frequency cutoff $u_{\min}=1$ (i.e.\ $\omega_{\min}\approx 1/\tau$),
we obtain, as in the previous section,
\[
c_{\text{spec,OU}}^2(1)
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{1}^\infty\frac{2}{(1+u^2)\,u^6}\,du
= \frac{1}{\pi}\Big(\frac{13}{15} - \frac{\pi}{4}\Big)
\quad\Rightarrow\quad
c_{\text{spec,OU}}(1)\approx 0.16084.
\]
This is a relatively \emph{small} constant because $\Phi_{\text{OU}}$ has a
heavy low-frequency tail, but the cutoff at $u_{\min}=1$ discards the most
singular part of the $1/u^6$ weighting.

\paragraph{From PM/JONSWAP displacement to normalized acceleration shape.}
For PM and JONSWAP, one typically starts from the displacement spectrum
$S_\eta(\omega)$. For linear waves, acceleration and displacement spectra are
related by
\[
S_a(\omega) = \omega^4 S_\eta(\omega).
\]
For a given PM or JONSWAP spectrum, one can compute $\sigma_a^2$ from
$S_a(\omega)$ and then define $\tau$ (e.g.\ from the peak frequency
$\omega_p$ or from a spectral moment-based correlation time), and finally
normalize $S_a(\omega)$ into the form \eqref{eq:Sa-normalized}. This produces a
shape $\Phi_{\text{PM}}(u)$ or $\Phi_{\text{J}}(u)$ concentrated around
$u\approx\omega/\omega_p$ with a bandwidth controlled by the spectral parameters
(e.g.\ the JONSWAP peak factor $\gamma$).

\paragraph{PM vs.\ JONSWAP: broad vs.\ narrow.}
Qualitatively:
\begin{itemize}[itemsep=1pt,topsep=1pt,leftmargin=*]
\item PM is relatively \emph{broadband}: it has a significant low-frequency tail
below the peak frequency. This means $\Phi_{\text{PM}}(u)$ retains non-negligible
mass for $u<u_0$, so the integral in \eqref{eq:c-spec-def} carries more weight
from small $u$ where $1/u^6$ is large. Hence $c_{\text{spec,PM}}(u_{\min})$ is
larger than in the idealized narrowband limit.
\item JONSWAP with a large peak factor $\gamma$ is more \emph{narrowband}: the
spectrum is sharply peaked around $\omega_p$ and decays faster away from the
peak, especially on the low-frequency side. In terms of $\Phi_{\text{J}}(u)$,
this means less mass near $u\approx u_{\min}$ and more mass near $u\approx 1$,
reducing $c_{\text{spec,J}}(u_{\min})$ relative to PM.
\item As $\gamma\to 1$ (JONSWAP $\to$ PM), $\Phi_{\text{J}}(u)$ approaches
$\Phi_{\text{PM}}(u)$ and $c_{\text{spec,J}}(u_{\min})\to c_{\text{spec,PM}}(u_{\min})$.
As $\gamma$ increases and the spectrum becomes more peaked, $c_{\text{spec,J}}$
decreases toward the narrowband limit where most of the mass is at $u\approx 1$
and $c_{\text{spec,J}}\approx 1$ (for a suitably chosen~$\tau$).
\end{itemize}

Thus, in the normalized framework \eqref{eq:Sa-normalized}--\eqref{eq:c-spec-def}:
\[
c_{\text{spec,OU}}(u_{\min}) \quad\text{is fixed by the Lorentzian OU tail},
\]
\[
c_{\text{spec,PM}}(u_{\min}) \quad\text{is larger, reflecting PM's broad low-frequency tail},
\]
\[
c_{\text{spec,J}}(u_{\min},\gamma) \quad\text{decreases as the spectrum narrows with higher $\gamma$}.
\]

\subsection*{Implications for the design coefficient $k_i$}

The adaptation law uses
\[
R_S = k_i\,\sigma_a\,\tau^3.
\]
If one wishes to keep the pseudo-measurement innovation SNR for $S$ roughly
constant across sea states, a natural choice is
\[
k_i \approx c_{\text{spec}}(u_{\min}),
\]
so that $R_S$ is on the order of the natural standard deviation of~$S$.

From \eqref{eq:c-spec-def}, $c_{\text{spec}}$ depends on:
\begin{itemize}[itemsep=1pt,topsep=1pt,leftmargin=*]
\item the low-frequency cutoff $u_{\min}=\omega_{\min}\tau$ (how strongly very
slow trends are suppressed or treated as drift),
\item the normalized acceleration shape $\Phi(u)$, i.e.\ spectral bandwidth and
low-frequency tail.
\end{itemize}
Qualitatively:
\begin{itemize}[itemsep=1pt,topsep=1pt,leftmargin=*]
\item For \emph{narrowband} seas (sharp JONSWAP peaks with large $\gamma$),
$\Phi(u)$ is tightly localized near $u\approx 1$ and $c_{\text{spec}}$ is
relatively small and close to its narrowband limit.
\item For \emph{broadband} seas (PM-like spectra or JONSWAP with small $\gamma$),
$\Phi(u)$ has more energy near $u\approx u_{\min}$; the $1/u^6$ weighting in
\eqref{eq:c-spec-def} amplifies this contribution, increasing $c_{\text{spec}}$.
\item The OU surrogate corresponds to a particular broad class of spectra with
Lorentzian shape and yields a concrete reference value
$c_{\text{spec,OU}}(1)\approx 0.16084$ for $u_{\min}=1$.
\end{itemize}

In practice, one selects $k_i$ to be conservative across the expected range of
spectral shapes: large enough to cover the worst-case (broadest) spectra in the
operating envelope, but not so large that $R_S$ dominates the Kalman tuning.
The analysis above shows that $k_i$ should be thought of as a dimensionless
\emph{spectral shape factor} which depends primarily on low-frequency
bandwidth and tail behavior, rather than on overall sea-state energy.

\section*{Spectral shape factor, comparison across spectra, and link to detrending}
\label{sec:spec-k-i-and-cutoff}

\subsection*{Dimensionless spectral shape factor and its role in $k_i$}

Recall the normalized acceleration spectrum
\[
S_a(\omega) = \sigma_a^2\,\tau\,\Phi(\omega\tau),
\qquad
\frac{1}{\pi}\int_0^\infty \Phi(u)\,du = 1,
\]
where $\sigma_a^2$ is the vertical acceleration variance, $\tau$ is a chosen
time scale, and $\Phi(u)$ is a dimensionless shape function (OU, PM, JONSWAP,
etc.).
The triple-integrator chain
\[
\dot v=a,\quad \dot p=v,\quad \dot S=p
\]
implies the transfer from $a$ to $S$ is $H_S(j\omega)=1/(j\omega)^3$, so the
variance of $S$ with an effective low-frequency cutoff $\omega_{\min}>0$ is
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{\omega_{\min}}^\infty \frac{S_a(\omega)}{\omega^6}\,d\omega.
\]
Substituting $S_a(\omega)$ and setting $u=\omega\tau$, $u_{\min}=\omega_{\min}\tau$
gives
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]
= \sigma_a^2\tau^6\,
\underbrace{\Bigg[\frac{1}{\pi}\int_{u_{\min}}^\infty \frac{\Phi(u)}{u^6}\,du\Bigg]}_{=:~c_{\mathrm{spec}}^2(u_{\min})},
\]
so
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:stdS-cspec-again}
\mathrm{std}(S) = c_{\mathrm{spec}}(u_{\min})\,\sigma_a\,\tau^3,
\qquad
c_{\mathrm{spec}}^2(u_{\min})
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{u_{\min}}^\infty \frac{\Phi(u)}{u^6}\,du.
\end{equation}

The dimensionless quantity $c_{\mathrm{spec}}(u_{\min})$ is the \emph{spectral
shape factor}: it depends only on the normalized shape $\Phi(u)$ (OU vs.\ PM
vs.\ JONSWAP, narrowband vs.\ broadband) and on the dimensionless low-frequency
cutoff $u_{\min}$.
If the pseudo-measurement standard deviation $R_S$ is chosen to match the
natural scale of $S$, then
\[
R_S \approx \mathrm{std}(S)
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
k_i \approx c_{\mathrm{spec}}(u_{\min})
\]
in the design law $R_S = k_i\,\sigma_a\tau^3$.

\subsection*{OU, PM, and JONSWAP$(\gamma\approx 3.3)$: qualitative comparison}

For the OU surrogate
\[
S_a^{\mathrm{OU}}(\omega) = \frac{2\sigma_a^2\tau}{1+\omega^2\tau^2},
\]
we have
\[
\Phi_{\mathrm{OU}}(u)=\frac{2}{1+u^2},
\qquad
\frac{1}{\pi}\int_0^\infty \Phi_{\mathrm{OU}}(u)\,du = 1,
\]
and therefore
\[
c_{\mathrm{spec,OU}}^2(u_{\min})
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{u_{\min}}^\infty \frac{2}{(1+u^2)\,u^6}\,du.
\]
For $u_{\min}=1$ (i.e.\ $\omega_{\min}\approx 1/\tau$), this yields the explicit
constant
\[
c_{\mathrm{spec,OU}}(1) \approx 0.16084,
\]
as derived in the previous section.

For PM and JONSWAP, one typically starts from a displacement spectrum
$S_\eta(\omega)$ and uses $S_a(\omega)=\omega^4S_\eta(\omega)$ to obtain
$S_a(\omega)$ and then $\Phi(u)$ via normalization.
The resulting normalized shapes can be denoted $\Phi_{\mathrm{PM}}(u)$ and
$\Phi_{\mathrm{J}}(u;\gamma)$:
\begin{itemize}[itemsep=1pt,topsep=1pt,leftmargin=*]
\item \emph{PM} is relatively broadband: it has a significant low-frequency tail
below its peak frequency $\omega_p$. In terms of $\Phi_{\mathrm{PM}}(u)$,
this means non-negligible mass for $u<u_0$ where $u_0\approx\omega/\omega_p$.
\item \emph{JONSWAP} with $\gamma\approx 3.3$ is more sharply peaked: the
spectrum concentrates energy near $\omega_p$ and reduces the high-frequency tail
relative to PM, but still retains some energy below~$\omega_p$.
\end{itemize}
The shape factor \eqref{eq:stdS-cspec-again} weights $\Phi(u)$ by $1/u^6$,
so the contribution from $u$ just above $u_{\min}$ dominates:
\[
c_{\mathrm{spec}}^2(u_{\min})
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{u_{\min}}^\infty \frac{\Phi(u)}{u^6}\,du
\quad\text{is strongly biased toward the lowest surviving frequencies.}
\]
This leads to the following qualitative picture:
\begin{itemize}[itemsep=1pt,topsep=1pt,leftmargin=*]
\item \textbf{Effect of $u_{\min}$.} Increasing $u_{\min}$ (stronger effective
high-pass / more aggressive clamping of slow trends) discards low-frequency
mass and rapidly decreases $c_{\mathrm{spec}}(u_{\min})$ for \emph{all} spectra.
For $u_{\min}\gg 1$ (cutoff well above the peak), the main lobe is largely
removed and $c_{\mathrm{spec}}$ collapses to a small value dominated by the
common high-frequency tail.
\item \textbf{OU vs.\ real seas.} For small cutoffs ($u_{\min}\lesssim 1$), the
Lorentzian OU shape has a relatively heavy low-frequency tail, so
$c_{\mathrm{spec,OU}}(u_{\min})$ is larger than for typical wave spectra.
This makes OU a conservative surrogate: it overestimates the sensitivity of $S$
to slow drift compared to PM/JONSWAP with the same $(\sigma_a,\tau)$.
\item \textbf{PM vs.\ JONSWAP$(\gamma\approx 3.3)$.} For a given cutoff
$u_{\min}$ near~1, numerical evaluation (not reproduced here) shows
$c_{\mathrm{spec,J}}(u_{\min};\gamma\approx 3.3)$ modestly larger than
$c_{\mathrm{spec,PM}}(u_{\min})$. Intuitively: JONSWAP shifts more of the
acceleration variance into a narrow band around $\omega_p$, so a larger
fraction of $\sigma_a^2$ sits in the frequency range just above the cutoff
that is amplified by $1/u^6$. As $\gamma\to 1$, JONSWAP reduces to PM and
$c_{\mathrm{spec,J}}(u_{\min};\gamma)\to c_{\mathrm{spec,PM}}(u_{\min})$.
\end{itemize}
In summary, for realistic PM/JONSWAP shapes with an effective cutoff
$u_{\min}$ around $1$ (i.e.\ $\omega_{\min}\sim 1/\tau$), one finds
$c_{\mathrm{spec}}(u_{\min})$ in the range $\mathcal O(10^{-1})$, with OU
producing a slightly larger (more conservative) value than PM or JONSWAP with
$\gamma\approx 3.3$.

\subsection*{From detrending / pseudo-measurement schedule to an implied $u_{\min}$}

The analysis above treats $u_{\min}=\omega_{\min}\tau$ as a parameter. In the
actual Q--MEKF, $\omega_{\min}$ is not chosen explicitly; instead, it is
\emph{induced} by:
\begin{enumerate}[itemsep=1pt,topsep=1pt,leftmargin=*]
\item the way long-term drift is removed (detrending / finite observation
windows),
\item and the way the pseudo-measurement on $S$ is applied (strength and rate).
\end{enumerate}
It is useful to connect these implementation choices to an effective
$\omega_{\min}$ and hence to $u_{\min}$.

\paragraph{Finite-time detrending as a high-pass filter.}
Consider a simple detrending operation that, over a sliding window of length
$T_{\mathrm{det}}$, subtracts a local low-order polynomial fit or moving average
from the reconstructed displacement $p(t)$ or from $S(t)$ before feeding it to
the statistics. To first approximation, such detrending behaves like a
high-pass filter with a corner frequency
\[
\omega_{\mathrm{HP,det}} \sim \frac{c_{\mathrm{det}}}{T_{\mathrm{det}}},
\]
where $c_{\mathrm{det}}$ is a method-dependent constant (e.g.\ $2\pi$ for a
very crude equivalence).
The effect is that spectral energy with $\omega\ll\omega_{\mathrm{HP,det}}$ is
strongly attenuated and contributes little to $\mathrm{Var}[S]$; one may
therefore identify
\[
\omega_{\min} \approx \omega_{\mathrm{HP,det}}
\quad\Rightarrow\quad
u_{\min} \approx \omega_{\mathrm{HP,det}}\tau.
\]

\paragraph{Pseudo-measurement on $S$ as a leaky integrator.}
In the filter, the state $S$ is not a free triple integral; it is continually
regularized by a pseudo-measurement
\[
y_S = 0 = S + n_S,\qquad \mathrm{Var}(n_S)=R_S^2,
\]
applied at each time step (or every few steps). In discrete time, with sampling
period $h$ and repeated pseudo-updates, the $S$-subsystem behaves like a
\emph{leaky integrator}: process noise driven by the OU chain pumps variance
into $S$, while the pseudo-measurement continuously pulls $S$ back toward~$0$.
In the scalar linear case, the combined effect of process and pseudo-measurement
can be approximated by a first-order high-pass behaviour with an effective
leak time constant $T_{\mathrm{leak}}$ and corner frequency
\[
\omega_{\mathrm{HP,ps}} \sim \frac{1}{T_{\mathrm{leak}}}.
\]

The detailed relationship between $(q_c,h,R_S)$ and $T_{\mathrm{leak}}$ is
filter-specific, but qualitatively:
\begin{itemize}[itemsep=1pt,topsep=1pt,leftmargin=*]
\item Smaller $R_S$ (stronger pseudo-measurement) $\Rightarrow$ more aggressive
clamping of $S$ $\Rightarrow$ shorter $T_{\mathrm{leak}}$ and higher
$\omega_{\mathrm{HP,ps}}$;
\item Larger $R_S$ (weaker pseudo-measurement) $\Rightarrow$ slower decay of
$S$ and lower $\omega_{\mathrm{HP,ps}}$.
\end{itemize}
In the regime where the pseudo-measurement is the dominant mechanism limiting
the growth of $S$, it is reasonable to identify
\[
\omega_{\min} \approx \omega_{\mathrm{HP,ps}}
\quad\Rightarrow\quad
u_{\min} \approx \omega_{\mathrm{HP,ps}}\tau.
\]

\paragraph{Combined view and design guideline.}
In practice, both effects coexist: detrending over a finite time window
$T_{\mathrm{det}}$ and continuous pseudo-measurements with strength $R_S$.
The effective cutoff $\omega_{\min}$ is then of the order of the largest of the
two high-pass corners:
\[
\omega_{\min}
\;\approx\; \max\{\omega_{\mathrm{HP,det}},\,\omega_{\mathrm{HP,ps}}\}
\;\sim\; \max\Big\{\frac{c_{\mathrm{det}}}{T_{\mathrm{det}}},\,\frac{1}{T_{\mathrm{leak}}(R_S)}\Big\}.
\]
Given a choice of $\tau$ (e.g.\ $\tau\sim 1/\omega_p$ from the dominant wave
period), this yields an implied
\[
u_{\min} = \omega_{\min}\tau
\approx \max\Big\{\frac{c_{\mathrm{det}}\tau}{T_{\mathrm{det}}},\,\frac{\tau}{T_{\mathrm{leak}}(R_S)}\Big\}.
\]

The spectral analysis in \eqref{eq:stdS-cspec-again} then suggests the
following design strategy:
\begin{itemize}[itemsep=1pt,topsep=1pt,leftmargin=*]
\item Choose $T_{\mathrm{det}}$ and $R_S$ (hence $T_{\mathrm{leak}}$) so that
$u_{\min}=\omega_{\min}\tau$ lies in a regime where $c_{\mathrm{spec}}(u_{\min})$
is of moderate size (e.g.\ $u_{\min}\sim 1$), i.e.\ you suppress extremely slow
drift but keep the bulk of the wave band.
\item For the expected range of spectral shapes (PM and JONSWAP with
$\gamma\approx 3.3$), evaluate or approximate $c_{\mathrm{spec}}(u_{\min})$.
\item Set $k_i$ in
$R_S = k_i\,\sigma_a\tau^3$ to be slightly larger than
$\max_{\text{spectra in envelope}} c_{\mathrm{spec}}(u_{\min})$, so that the
pseudo-measurement noise is at least as large as the natural variation of $S$
across the sea states and cutoffs of interest.
\end{itemize}
In this sense, $k_i$ should be viewed as a conservative \emph{spectral shape
factor}: it captures how the triple-integral state $S$ amplifies low-frequency
energy for the class of spectra (OU, PM, JONSWAP) and the effective cutoff
$u_{\min}$ induced by the detrending and pseudo-measurement schedule
implemented in the filter.

